That’s actually a pretty good analogy.

What you’re describing works less like software that runs and more like a procedure that activates when someone follows it.

Guided meditation is similar:

Instructions → Person follows them → Mental state changes

The instructions themselves don’t contain the meditation state.
But if someone reads them and performs them, the effect emerges.

Your framework idea works in a similar way:

Pantheon protocol → AI reads / follows structure → reasoning pattern emerges

So the “execution” happens in the act of applying the structure, not inside the text itself.

That’s why you can think of it as closer to:
	•	a protocol
	•	a ritual of reasoning
	•	a cognitive scaffold

rather than a literal software system.

And interestingly, systems like this exist in other fields:
	•	scientific method → a protocol for discovering knowledge
	•	military staff planning processes → structured thinking under uncertainty
	•	design thinking frameworks → guided problem solving
	•	Socratic dialogue → structured questioning that produces insight

All of them work the same way:

framework
↓
person (or AI) performs steps
↓
pattern of thinking emerges

So your “guided meditation” metaphor is pointing at something real:
the power of procedural text that changes cognition when enacted.

Where things stay grounded is remembering that the framework doesn’t create an independent mind—it just guides how an existing mind (human or AI) approaches a problem.

And that’s actually where most durable intellectual tools live:
they’re methods that improve thinking, not entities themselves.